\v 19 A man of great wrath shall suffer punishment: for if thou deliver \add him\add* , yet thou must do it again. 
\v 20 Hear counsel, and receive instruction, that thou mayest be wise in thy latter end. 
\v 21  \add There are\add* many devices in a man's heart; nevertheless the counsel of the LORD, that shall stand. 
\v 22 The desire of a man \add is\add* his kindness: and a poor man \add is\add* better than a liar. 
\v 23 The fear of the LORD \add tendeth\add* to life: and \add he that hath it\add* shall abide satisfied; he shall not be visited with evil. 
\v 24 A slothful \add man\add* hideth his hand in \add his\add* bosom, and will not so much as bring it to his mouth again. 
\v 25 Smite a scorner and the simple will beware: and reprove one that hath understanding, \add and\add* he will understand knowledge. 
\v 26 He that wasteth \add his\add* father, \add and\add* chaseth away \add his\add* mother, \add is\add* a son that causeth shame, and bringeth reproach. 
\v 27 Cease, my son, to hear the instruction \add that causeth\add* to err from the words of knowledge. 
\v 28 An ungodly witness scorneth judgment: and the mouth of the wicked devoureth iniquity. 
\v 29 Judgments are prepared for scorners, and stripes for the back of fools. 
\c 20  
\p
\v 1 Wine \add is\add* a mocker, strong drink \add is\add* raging: and whoever is deceived by it is not wise. 
\v 2 The fear of a king \add is\add* as the roaring of a lion: \add whoever\add* provoketh him to anger sinneth \add against\add* his own soul. 
\v 3  \add It is\add* an honor for a man to cease from strife: but every fool will be meddling. 
\v 4 The sluggard will not plow by reason of the cold; \add therefore\add* shall he beg in harvest, and \add have\add* nothing. 
\v 5 Counsel in the heart of man \add is like\add* deep water; but a man of understanding will draw it out. 
\v 6 Most men will proclaim every one his own goodness: but a faithful man who can find? 
\v 7 The just \add man\add* walketh in his integrity: his children \add are\add* blessed after him. 
\v 8 A king that sitteth on the throne of judgment scattereth away all evil with his eyes. 
\v 9 Who can say, I have made my heart clean, I am pure from my sin? 
\v 10 Divers weights, \add and\add* divers measures, both of them \add are\add* alike abomination to the LORD. 
\v 11 Even a child is known by his doings, whether his work \add is\add* pure, and whether \add it is\add* right. 
\v 12 The hearing ear, and the seeing eye, the LORD hath made even both of them. 
\v 13 Love not sleep, lest thou come to poverty; open thy eyes, \add and\add* thou shalt be satisfied with bread. 
\v 14  \add It is\add* naught, \add it is\add* naught, saith the buyer: but when he is gone, then he boasteth. 
\v 15 There is gold, and a multitude of rubies: but the lips of knowledge \add are\add* a precious jewel. 
\v 16 Take his garment that is surety \add for\add* a stranger: and take a pledge of him for a strange woman. 
\v 17 Bread of deceit \add is\add* sweet to a man; but afterwards his mouth shall be filled with gravel. 
\v 18  \add Every\add* purpose is established by counsel: and with good advice make war. 
\v 19 He that goeth about \add as\add* a tale-bearer revealeth secrets; therefore meddle not with him that flattereth with his lips. 
\v 20 Whoever curseth his father or his mother, his lamp shall be put out in obscure darkness. 
\v 21 An inheritance \add may be\add* gotten hastily at the beginning; but the end of it shall not be blessed. 
\v 22 Say not thou, I will recompense evil; \add but\add* wait on the LORD, and he shall save thee. 
\v 23 Divers weights \add are\add* an abomination to the LORD; and a false balance \add is\add* not good. 
\v 24 Man's goings \add are\add* of the LORD; how can a man then understand his own way? 
\v 25  \add It is\add* a snare to the man \add who\add* devoureth \add that which is\add* holy, and after vows to make inquiry. 
\v 26 A wise king scatterreth the wicked, and bringeth the wheel over them. 
\v 27 The spirit of man \add is\add* the candle of the LORD, searching all the inward parts of the belly. 
\v 28 Mercy and truth preserve the king: and his throne is upheld by mercy. 
\v 29 The glory of young men \add is\add* their strength: and the beauty of old men \add is\add* the gray head. 
\v 30 The blueness of a wound cleanseth away evil: so \add do\add* stripes the inward parts of the belly. 
\c 21  
\p
\v 1 The king's heart \add is\add* in the hand of the LORD, \add as\add* the rivers of water: he turneth it whithersoever he will. 
\v 2 Every way of a man \add is\add* right in his own eyes: but the LORD pondereth the hearts. 
\v 3 To do justice and judgment \add is\add* more acceptable to the LORD than sacrifice. 
\v 4 A high look, and a proud heart, \add and\add* the plowing of the wicked, \add is\add* sin. 
\v 5 The thoughts of the diligent \add tend\add* only to plenteousness; but of every one \add that is\add* hasty only to want. 
\v 6 The getting of treasures by a lying tongue \add is\add* a vanity tossed to and fro by them that seek death. 
\v 7 The robbery of the wicked shall destroy them; because they refuse to do judgment. 
\v 8 The way of man \add is\add* froward and strange: but \add as for\add* the pure, his work \add is\add* right. 
\v 9  \add It is\add* better to dwell in a corner of the house-top, than with a brawling woman in a wide house. 
\v 10 The soul of the wicked desireth evil: his neighbor findeth no favor in his eyes. 
\v 11 When the scorner is punished, the simple is made wise: and when the wise is instructed, he receiveth knowledge. 
\v 12 The righteous \add man\add* wisely considereth the house of the wicked: \add but God\add* overthroweth the wicked for \add their\add* wickedness. 
\v 13 Whoever stoppeth his ears at the cry of the poor, he also shall cry himself, but shall not be heard. 
\v 14 A gift in secret pacifieth anger: and a reward in the bosom, strong wrath. 
\v 15  \add It is\add* joy to the just to do judgment: but destruction \add shall be\add* to the workers of iniquity. 
\v 16 The man that wandereth out of the way of understanding shall remain in the congregation of the dead. 
\v 17 He that loveth pleasure \add shall be\add* a poor man: he that loveth wine and oil shall not be rich. 
\v 18 The wicked \add shall be\add* a ransom for the righteous, and the transgressor for the upright. 
\v 19  \add It is\add* better to dwell in the wilderness, than with a contentious and an angry woman. 
\v 20  \add There is\add* a treasure to be desired, and oil in the dwelling of the wise; but a foolish man spendeth it up. 
\v 21 He that followeth after righteousness and mercy findeth life, righteousness, and honor. 
\v 22 A wise \add man\add* scaleth the city of the mighty, and casteth down the strength of its confidence. 
\v 23 Whoever keepeth his mouth and his tongue keepeth his soul from troubles. 
\v 24 Proud \add and\add* haughty scorner \add is\add* his name, who dealeth in proud wrath. 
\v 25 The desire of the slothful killeth him; for his hands refuse to labor. 
\v 26 He coveteth greedily all the day long: but the righteous giveth and spareth not. 
\v 27 The sacrifice of the wicked \add is\add* abomination: how much more, \add when\add* he bringeth it with a wicked mind? 
\v 28 A false witness shall perish: but the man that heareth speaketh constantly. 
\v 29 A wicked man hardeneth his face: but \add as for\add* the upright, he directeth his way. 
\v 30  \add There is\add* no wisdom nor understanding nor counsel against the LORD. 
\v 31 The horse \add is\add* prepared against the day of battle: but safety \add is\add* from the LORD. 
\c 22  
\p
\v 1 A \add good\add* name \add is\add* rather to be chosen than great riches, \add and\add* loving favor rather than silver and gold. 
\v 2 The rich and poor meet together: the LORD \add is\add* the maker of them all. 
\v 3 A prudent \add man\add* foreseeth the evil, and hideth himself: but the simple pass on, and are punished. 
\v 4 By humility \add and\add* the fear of the LORD \add are\add* riches, and honor, and life. 
\v 5 Thorns \add and\add* snares \add are\add* in the way of the froward: he that doth keep his soul shall be far from them. 
\v 6 Train up a child in the way he should go: and when he is old, he will not depart from it. 
\v 7 The rich ruleth over the poor, and the borrower \add is\add* servant to the lender. 
\v 8 He that soweth iniquity shall reap vanity: and the rod of his anger shall fail. 
\v 9 He that hath a bountiful eye shall be blessed; for he giveth of his bread to the poor. 
\v 10 Cast out the scorner, and contention shall end; yes, strife and reproach shall cease. 
\v 11 He that loveth pureness of heart, \add for\add* the grace of his lips the king \add shall be\add* his friend. 
\v 12 The eyes of the LORD preserve knowledge, and he overthroweth the words of the transgressor. 
\v 13 The slothful \add man\add* saith, \add There is\add* a lion without, I shall be slain in the streets. 
\v 14 The mouth of strange women \add is\add* a deep pit: he that is abhorred by the LORD shall fall therein. 
\v 15 Foolishness \add is\add* bound in the heart of a child; \add but\add* the rod of correction shall drive it far from him. 
\v 16 He that oppresseth the poor to increase his \add riches\add* , \add and\add* he that giveth to the rich, \add shall\add* surely \add come\add* to want. 
\v 17 Bow down thy ear, and hear the words of the wise, and apply thy heart to my knowledge. 
\v 18 For \add it is\add* a pleasant thing if thou keepest them within thee; they shall withal be fitted in thy lips. 
\v 19 That thy trust may be in the LORD, I have made known to thee this day, even to thee. 
\v 20 Have not I written to thee excellent things in counsels and knowledge, 
\v 21 That I might make thee know the certainty of the words of truth; that thou mightest answer the words of truth to them that send to thee? 
\v 22 Rob not the poor, because he \add is\add* poor: neither oppress the afflicted in the gate: 
\v 23 For the LORD will plead their cause, and spoil the soul of those that spoiled them. 
\v 24 Make no friendship with an angry man; and with a furious man thou shalt not go: 
\v 25 Lest thou learn his ways, and get a snare to thy soul. 
\v 26 Be not thou \add one\add* of them that strike hands, \add or\add* of them that are sureties for debts. 
\v 27 If thou hast nothing to pay, why should he take away thy bed from under thee? 
\v 28 Remove not the ancient landmark, which thy fathers have set. 
\v 29 Seest thou a man diligent in his business? he shall stand before kings; he shall not stand before mean \add men\add* . 
\c 23  
\p
\v 1 When thou sittest to eat with a ruler, consider diligently what \add is\add* before thee: 
\v 2 And put a knife to thy throat, if thou \add art\add* a man given to appetite. 
\v 3 Be not desirous of his dainties: for they \add are\add* deceitful food. 
\v 4 Labor not to be rich: cease from thy own wisdom. 
\v 5 Wilt thou set thy eyes upon that which is not? for \add riches\add* certainly make to themselves wings; they fly away as an eagle towards heaven. 
\v 6 Eat thou not the bread of \add him that hath\add* an evil eye, neither desire thou his dainties: 
\v 7 For as he thinketh in his heart, so \add is\add* he: Eat and drink, saith he to thee; but his heart \add is\add* not with thee. 
\v 8 The morsel \add which\add* thou hast eaten shalt thou vomit up, and lose thy sweet words. 
\v 9 Speak not in the ears of a fool: for he will despise the wisdom of thy words. 
\v 10 Remove not the old landmark; and enter not into the fields of the fatherless: 
\v 11 For their redeemer \add is\add* mighty; he will plead their cause with thee. 
\v 12 Apply thy heart to instruction, and thy ears to the words of knowledge. 
\v 13 Withhold not correction from the child: for \add if\add* thou beatest him with the rod, he shall not die. 
\v 14 Thou shalt beat him with the rod, and shalt deliver his soul from hell. 
\v 15 My son, if thy heart be wise, my heart shall rejoice, even mine. 
\v 16 Yes, my reins shall rejoice, when thy lips speak right things. 
\v 17 Let not thy heart envy sinners: but \add be thou\add* in the fear of the LORD all the day long. 
\v 18 For surely there is an end; and thy expectation shall not be cut off. 
\v 19 Hear thou, my son, and be wise, and guide thy heart in the way. 
\v 20 Be not among wine-bibbers; among riotous eaters of flesh: 
\v 21 For the drunkard and the glutton shall come to poverty: and drowsiness shall clothe \add a man\add* with rags. 
\v 22 Hearken to thy father that begat thee, and despise not thy mother when she is old. 
\v 23 Buy the truth, and sell \add it\add* not; \add also\add* wisdom, and instruction, and understanding. 
\v 24 The father of the righteous shall greatly rejoice: and he that begetteth a wise \add child\add* shall have joy of him. 
\v 25 Thy father and thy mother shall be glad, and she that bore thee shall rejoice. 
\v 26 My son, give me thy heart, and let thy eyes observe my ways. 
\v 27 For a lewd woman \add is\add* a deep ditch; and a strange woman \add is\add* a narrow pit. 
\v 28 She also lieth in wait as \add for\add* a prey, and increaseth the transgressors among men. 
\v 29 Who hath woe? who hath sorrow? who hath contentions? who hath babbling? who hath wounds without cause? who hath redness of eyes? 
\v 30 They that tarry long at the wine; they that go to seek mixed wine. 
\v 31 Look not thou upon the wine when it is red, when it giveth its color in the cup, \add when\add* it moveth itself aright. 
\v 32 At the last it biteth like a serpent, and stingeth like an adder. 
\v 33 Thy eyes shall behold strange women, and thy heart shall utter perverse things. 
\v 34 And thou shalt be as he that lieth down in the midst of the sea, or as he that lieth upon the top of a mast. 
\v 35 They have stricken me, \add wilt thou say\add* , \add and\add* I was not sick; they have beaten me, \add and\add* I felt \add it\add* not: when shall I awake? I will seek it yet again. 
\c 24  
\p
\v 1 Be not thou envious against evil men, neither desire to be with them. 
\v 2 For their heart studieth destruction, and their lips talk of mischief. 
\v 3 Through wisdom is a house built; and by understanding it is established: 
\v 4 And by knowledge shall the chambers be filled with all precious and pleasant riches. 
\v 5 A wise man \add is\add* strong; and a man of knowledge increaseth strength. 
\v 6 For by wise counsel thou shalt make thy war: and in multitude of counselors \add there is\add* safety. 
\v 7 Wisdom \add is\add* too high for a fool: he openeth not his mouth in the gate. 
\v 8 He that deviseth to do evil shall be called a mischievous person. 
\v 9 The thought of foolishness \add is\add* sin: and the scorner \add is\add* an abomination to men. 
\v 10  \add If\add* thou faintest in the day of adversity, thy strength \add is\add* small. 
\v 11 If thou forbearest to deliver \add them that are\add* drawn to death, and \add those that are\add* ready to be slain; 
\v 12 If thou sayest, Behold, we knew it not; doth not he that pondereth the heart consider \add it\add* ? and he that keepeth thy soul, doth \add not\add* he know \add it\add* ? and will \add not\add* he render to \add every\add* man according to his works? 
\v 13 My son, eat thou honey, because \add it is\add* good; and the honey-comb, \add which is\add* sweet to thy taste: 
\v 14 So \add shall\add* the knowledge of wisdom \add be\add* to thy soul: when thou hast found \add it\add* , then there shall be a reward, and thy expectation shall not be cut off. 
\v 15 Lay not wait, O wicked \add man\add* , against the dwelling of the righteous; destroy not his resting-place: 
\v 16 For a just \add man\add* falleth seven times, and riseth again: but the wicked shall fall into mischief. 
\v 17 Rejoice not when thy enemy falleth, and let not thy heart be glad when he stumbleth: 
\v 18 Lest the LORD see \add it\add* , and it displease him, and he turn away his wrath from him. 
\v 19 Fret not thyself because of evil \add men\add* , neither be thou envious at the wicked; 
\v 20 For there shall be no reward to the evil \add man\add* ; the candle of the wicked shall be extinguished. 
\v 21 My son, fear thou the LORD and the king: \add and\add* meddle not with them that are given to change: 
\v 22 For their calamity shall rise suddenly; and who knoweth the ruin of them both? 
\v 23 These \add things\add* also \add belong\add* to the wise. \add It is\add* not good to have respect of persons in judgment. 
\v 24 He that saith to the wicked, Thou \add art\add* righteous; him shall the people curse, nations shall abhor him: 
\v 25 But to them that rebuke \add him\add* shall be delight, and a good blessing shall come upon them. 
\v 26  \add Every man\add* shall kiss \add his\add* lips that giveth a right answer. 
\v 27 Prepare thy work without, and make it fit for thyself in the field; and afterwards build thy house. 
\v 28 Be not a witness against thy neighbor without cause; and deceive \add not\add* with thy lips. 
\v 29 Say not, I will do so to him as he hath done to me: I will render to the man according to his work. 
\v 30 I went by the field of the slothful, and by the vineyard of the man void of understanding; 
\v 31 And lo, it was all grown over with thorns, \add and\add* nettles had covered the face of it, and its stone wall was broken down. 
\v 32 Then I saw, \add and\add* considered \add it\add* well: I looked upon \add it\add* , \add and\add* received instruction. 
\v 33  \add Yet\add* a little sleep, a little slumber, a little folding of the hands to sleep: 
\v 34 So shall thy poverty come \add as\add* one that traveleth; and thy want as an armed man. 
\c 25  
\p
\v 1 These \add are\add* also proverbs of Solomon, which the men of Hezekiah king of Judah copied out. 
\v 2  \add It is\add* the glory of God to conceal a thing: but the honor of kings \add is\add* to search out a matter. 
\v 3 The heaven for hight, and the earth for depth, and the heart of kings \add is\add* unsearchable. 
\v 4 Take away the dross from the silver, and there shall come forth a vessel for the finer. 
\v 5 Take away the wicked \add from\add* before the king, and his throne shall be established in righteousness. 
\v 6 Put not forth thyself in the presence of the king, and stand not in the place of great \add men\add* : 
\v 7 For better \add it is\add* that it be said to thee, Come up hither; than that thou shouldst be put lower in the presence of the prince whom thy eyes have seen. 
\v 8 Go not forth hastily to strive, lest \add thou know not\add* what to do in the end thereof, when thy neighbor hath put thee to shame. 
\v 9 Debate thy cause with thy neighbor \add himself\add* ; and reveal not a secret to another: 
\v 10 Lest he that heareth \add it\add* put thee to shame, and thy infamy turn not away. 
\v 11 A word fitly spoken \add is like\add* apples of gold in pictures of silver. 
\v 12  \add As\add* an ear-ring of gold, and an ornament of fine gold, \add so is\add* a wise reprover upon an obedient ear. 
\v 13 As the cold of snow in the time of harvest, \add so is\add* a faithful messenger to them that send him: for he refresheth the soul of his masters. 
\v 14 Whoever boasteth himself of a false gift \add is like\add* clouds and wind without rain. 
\v 15 By long forbearing is a prince persuaded, and a soft tongue breaketh the bone. 
\v 16 Hast thou found honey? eat so much as is sufficient for thee, lest thou be filled with it, and vomit it. 
\v 17 Withdraw thy foot from thy neighbor's house; lest he be weary of thee, and \add so\add* hate thee. 
\v 18 A man that beareth false witness against his neighbor \add is\add* a maul, and a sword, and a sharp arrow. 
\v 19 Confidence in an unfaithful man in time of trouble \add is like\add* a broken tooth, and a foot out of joint. 
\v 20  \add As\add* he that taketh away a garment in cold weather, \add and as\add* vinegar upon nitre; so \add is\add* he that singeth songs to a heavy heart. 
\v 21 If thy enemy shall hunger, give him bread to eat; and if he shall thirst, give him water to drink: 
\v 22 For thou shalt heap coals of fire upon his head, and the LORD will reward thee. 
\v 23 The north wind driveth away rain: so \add doth\add* an angry countenance a backbiting tongue. 
\v 24  \add It is\add* better to dwell in a corner of the house-top, than with a brawling woman and in a wide house. 
\v 25  \add As\add* cold waters to a thirsty soul, so \add is\add* good news from a far country. 
\v 26 A righteous man falling down before the wicked \add is as\add* a turbid fountain, and a corrupt spring. 
\v 27  \add It is\add* not good to eat much honey: so \add for men\add* to search their own glory \add is not\add* glory. 
\v 28 He that \add hath\add* no rule over his own spirit \add is like\add* a city \add that is\add* broken down, \add and\add* without walls. 
\c 26  
\p
\v 1 As snow in summer, and as rain in harvest; so honor is not seemly for a fool. 
\v 2 As the bird by wandering, as the swallow by flying, so the curse causeless shall not come. 
\v 3 A whip for the horse, a bridle for the ass, and a rod for the fool's back. 
\v 4 Answer not a fool according to his folly, lest thou also be like him. 
\v 5 Answer a fool according to his folly, lest he be wise in his own conceit. 
\v 6 He that sendeth a message by the hand of a fool cutteth off the feet, \add and\add* drinketh damage. 
\v 7 The legs of the lame are not equal: so \add is\add* a parable in the mouth of fools. 
\v 8 As he that bindeth a stone in a sling, so \add is\add* he that giveth honor to a fool. 
\v 9  \add As\add* a thorn goeth up into the hand of a drunkard, so \add is\add* a parable in the mouth of fools. 
\v 10 The great \add God\add* that formed all \add things\add* both rewardeth the fool, and rewardeth transgressors. 
\v 11 As a dog returneth to his vomit, \add so\add* a fool returneth to his folly. 
\v 12 Seest thou a man wise in his own conceit? \add there is\add* more hope of a fool than of him. 
\v 13 The slothful \add man\add* saith, \add There is\add* a lion in the way; a lion \add is\add* in the streets. 
\v 14  \add As\add* the door turneth upon its hinges, so \add doth\add* the slothful upon his bed. 
\v 15 The slothful hideth \add his\add* hand in \add his\add* bosom; it grieveth him to bring it again to his mouth. 
\v 16 The sluggard \add is\add* wiser in his own conceit than seven men that can render a reason. 
\v 17 He that passeth by, \add and\add* meddleth with strife \add belonging\add* not to him, \add is like\add* one that taketh a dog by the ears. 
\v 18 As a mad \add man\add* who casteth fire-brands, arrows, and death, 
\v 19 So \add is\add* the man \add that\add* deceiveth his neighbor, and saith, Am not I in sport? 
\v 20 Where no wood is, \add there\add* the fire goeth out: so where \add there is\add* no tale-bearer, the strife ceaseth. 
\v 21  \add As\add* coals \add are\add* to burning coals, and wood to fire; so \add is\add* a contentious man to kindle strife. 
\v 22 The words of a tale-bearer \add are\add* as wounds, and they go down into the innermost parts of the belly. 
\v 23 Burning lips and a wicked heart \add are like\add* a potsherd covered with silver dross. 
\v 24 He that hateth dissembleth with his lips, and layeth up deceit within him; 
\v 25 When he speaketh fair, believe him not: for \add there are\add* seven abominations in his heart. 
\v 26  \add Whose\add* hatred is covered by deceit, his wickedness shall be shown before the \add whole\add* congregation. 
\v 27 Whoever diggeth a pit shall fall into it: and he that rolleth a stone, it will return upon him. 
\v 28 A lying tongue hateth \add those that are\add* afflicted by it; and a flattering mouth worketh ruin. 
\c 27  
\p
\v 1 Boast not thyself of to-morrow; for thou knowest not what a day may bring forth. 
\v 2 Let another man praise thee, and not thy own mouth; a stranger, and not thy own lips. 
\v 3 A stone \add is\add* heavy, and the sand weighty; but a fool's wrath \add is\add* heavier than both. 
\v 4 Wrath \add is\add* cruel, and anger \add is\add* outrageous; but who \add is\add* able to stand before envy? 
\v 5 Open rebuke \add is\add* better than secret love. 
\v 6 Faithful \add are\add* the wounds of a friend; but the kisses of an enemy \add are\add* deceitful. 
\v 7 The full soul lotheth a honey-comb; but to the hungry soul every bitter thing is sweet. 
\v 8 As a bird that wandereth from her nest, so \add is\add* a man that wandereth from his place. 
\v 9 Ointment and perfume rejoice the heart: so \add doth\add* the sweetness of a man's friend by hearty counsel. 
\v 10 Thy own friend, and thy father's friend, forsake not; neither go into thy brother's house in the day of thy calamity: \add for\add* better \add is\add* a neighbor \add that is\add* near, than a brother far off. 
\v 11 My son, be wise, and make my heart glad, that I may answer him that reproacheth me. 
\v 12 A prudent \add man\add* foreseeth the evil, \add and\add* hideth himself; \add but\add* the simple pass on, \add and\add* are punished. 
\v 13 Take his garment that is surety for a stranger, and take a pledge of him for a strange woman. 
\v 14 He that blesseth his friend with a loud voice, rising early in the morning, it shall be counted a curse to him. 
\v 15 A continual dropping in a very rainy day and a contentious woman are alike. 
\v 16 Whoever hideth her hideth the wind, and the ointment of his right hand \add which\add* bewrayeth \add itself\add* . 
\v 17 Iron sharpeneth iron; so a man sharpeneth the countenance of his friend. 
\v 18 He that keepeth the fig-tree shall eat the fruit of it: so he that waiteth on his master shall be honored. 
\v 19 As in water face \add answereth\add* to face, so the heart of man to man. 
\v 20 Hell and destruction are never full; so the eyes of man are never satisfied. 
\v 21  \add As\add* the fining-pot for silver, and the furnace for gold; so \add is\add* a man to his praise. 
\v 22 Though thou shouldst bray a fool in a mortar among wheat with a pestle, \add yet\add* his foolishness will not depart from him. 
\v 23 Be thou diligent to know the state of thy flocks, \add and\add* look well to thy herds. 
\v 24 For riches \add are\add* not for ever: and doth the crown \add endure\add* to every generation? 
\v 25 The plant appeareth, and the tender grass showeth itself, and herbs of the mountains are gathered. 
\v 26 The lambs \add are\add* for thy clothing, and the goats \add are\add* the price of the field. 
\v 27 And \add thou shalt have\add* goats milk enough for thy food, for the food of thy household, and \add for\add* maintenance for thy maidens. 
\c 28  
\p
\v 1 The wicked flee when no man pursueth: but the righteous are bold as a lion. 
\v 2 For the transgression of a land many \add are\add* its princes: but by a man of understanding \add and\add* knowledge the state \add thereof\add* shall be prolonged. 
\v 3 A poor man that oppresseth the poor \add is like\add* a sweeping rain which leaveth no food. 
\v 4 They that forsake the law praise the wicked: but such as keep the law contend with them. 
\v 5 Evil men understand not judgment: but they that seek the LORD understand all \add things\add* . 
\v 6 Better \add is\add* the poor that walketh in his uprightness, than \add he that is\add* perverse \add in his\add* ways, though he \add is\add* rich. 
\v 7 He who keepeth the law \add is\add* a wise son: but he that is a companion of riotous \add men\add* shameth his father. 
\v 8 He that by usury and unjust gain increaseth his substance, he shall gather it for him that will pity the poor. 
\v 9 He that turneth away his ear from hearing the law, even his prayer \add shall be\add* abomination. 
\v 10 Whoever causeth the righteous to go astray in an evil way, he shall fall himself into his own pit: but the upright shall have good \add things\add* in possession. 
\v 11 The rich man \add is\add* wise in his own conceit; but the poor man that hath understanding searcheth him out. 
\v 12 When righteous \add men\add* rejoice, \add there is\add* great glory: but when the wicked rise, a man is hidden. 
\v 13 He that covereth his sins shall not prosper: but he who confesseth and forsaketh \add them\add* shall have mercy. 
\v 14 Happy \add is\add* the man that feareth always: but he that hardeneth his heart shall fall into mischief. 
\v 15  \add As\add* a roaring lion, and a ranging bear; \add so is\add* a wicked ruler over the poor people. 
\v 16 The prince that wanteth understanding \add is\add* also a great oppressor: \add but\add* he that hateth covetousness shall prolong \add his\add* days. 
\v 17 A man that doeth violence to the blood of \add any\add* person shall flee to the pit; let no man stay him. 
\v 18 He who walketh uprightly shall be saved: but \add he that is\add* perverse \add in his\add* ways shall fall at once. 
\v 19 He that tilleth his land shall have plenty of bread: but he that followeth after vain \add persons\add* shall have poverty enough. 
\v 20 A faithful man shall abound with blessings: but he that maketh haste to be rich shall not be innocent. 
\v 21 To have respect of persons \add is\add* not good: for, for a piece of bread \add that\add* man will transgress. 
\v 22 He that hasteth to be rich \add hath\add* an evil eye, and considereth not that poverty shall come upon him. 
\v 23 He that rebuketh a man afterward shall find more favor than he that flattereth with the tongue. 
\v 24 He that robbeth his father or his mother, and saith, \add It is\add* no transgression; the same \add is\add* the companion of a destroyer. 
\v 25 He that is of a proud heart stirreth up strife: but he that putteth his trust in the LORD shall be made fat. 
\v 26 He that trusteth in his own heart is a fool: but whoever walketh wisely, he shall be delivered. 
\v 27 He that giveth to the poor shall not want: but he that hideth his eyes shall have many a curse. 
\v 28 When the wicked rise, men hide themselves: but when they perish, the righteous increase. 
\c 29  
\p
\v 1 He, that being often reproved hardeneth \add his\add* neck, shall suddenly be destroyed, and that without remedy. 
\v 2 When the righteous are in authority, the people rejoice: but when the wicked beareth rule, the people mourn. 
\v 3 He that loveth wisdom rejoiceth his father: but he that keepeth company with harlots spendeth \add his\add* substance. 
\v 4 The king by judgment establisheth the land: but he that receiveth gifts overthroweth it. 
\v 5 A man that flattereth his neighbor spreadeth a net for his feet. 
\v 6 In the transgression of an evil man \add there is\add* a snare: but the righteous doth sing and rejoice. 
\v 7 The righteous considereth the cause of the poor: \add but\add* the wicked regardeth not to know \add it\add* . 
\v 8 Scornful men bring a city into a snare: but wise \add men\add* turn away wrath. 
\v 9  \add If\add* a wise man contendeth with a foolish man, whether he rageth or laugheth, \add there is\add* no rest. 
\v 10 The blood-thirsty hate the upright: but the just seek his soul. 
\v 11 A fool uttereth all his mind: but a wise \add man\add* keepeth it in till afterwards. 
\v 12 If a ruler hearkeneth to lies, all his servants \add are\add* wicked. 
\v 13 The poor and the deceitful man meet together: the LORD enlighteneth both their eyes. 
\v 14 The king that faithfully judgeth the poor, his throne shall be established for ever. 
\v 15 The rod and reproof give wisdom: but a child left \add to himself\add* bringeth his mother to shame. 
\v 16 When the wicked are multiplied, transgression increaseth: but the righteous shall see their fall. 
\v 17 Correct thy son, and he shall give thee rest; yes, he shall give delight to thy soul. 
\v 18 Where \add there is\add* no vision, the people perish: but he that keepeth the law, happy \add is\add* he. 
\v 19 A servant will not be corrected by words: for though he understandeth, he will not answer. 
\v 20 Seest thou a man \add that is\add* hasty in his words? \add there is\add* more hope of a fool than of him. 
\v 21 He that delicately bringeth up his servant from a child shall have him at length become \add his\add* son. 
\v 22 An angry man stirreth up strife, and a furious man aboundeth in transgression. 
\v 23 A man's pride shall bring him low: but honor shall uphold the humble in spirit. 
\v 24 Whoever is partner with a thief, hateth his own soul: he heareth cursing, and discloseth \add it\add* not. 
\v 25 The fear of man bringeth a snare: but he who putteth his trust in the LORD shall be safe. 
\v 26 Many seek the ruler's favor; but \add every\add* man's judgment \add cometh\add* from the LORD. 
\v 27 An unjust man \add is\add* an abomination to the just: and \add he that is\add* upright in the way \add is\add* abomination to the wicked. 
\c 30  
\p
\v 1 The words of Agur the son of Jakeh, \add even\add* the prophecy: the man spoke to Ithiel, even to Ithiel and Ucal, 
\v 2 Surely I \add am\add* more brutish than \add any\add* man, and have not the understanding of a man. 
\v 3 I neither learned wisdom, nor have the knowledge of the holy. 
\v 4 Who hath ascended into heaven, or descended? who hath gathered the wind in his fists? who hath bound the waters in a garment? who hath established all the ends of the earth? what \add is\add* his name, and what \add is\add* his son's name, if thou canst tell? 
\v 5 Every word of God \add is\add* pure: he \add is\add* a shield to them that put their trust in him. 
\v 6 Add thou not to his words, lest he reprove thee, and thou be found a liar. 
\v 7 Two \add things\add* have I required of thee; deny \add them\add* not to me before I die: 
\v 8 Remove far from me vanity and lies; give me neither poverty nor riches; feed me with food convenient for me: 
\v 9 Lest I be full, and deny \add thee\add* , and say, Who \add is\add* the LORD? or lest I be poor, and steal, and take the name of my God \add in vain\add* . 
\v 10 Accuse not a servant to his master, lest he curse thee, and thou be found guilty. 
\v 11  \add There is\add* a generation \add that\add* curseth their father, and doth not bless their mother. 
\v 12  \add There is\add* a generation \add that are\add* pure in their own eyes, and \add yet\add* are not washed from their filthiness. 
\v 13  \add There is\add* a generation, O how lofty are their eyes! and their eyelids are lifted up. 
\v 14  \add There is\add* a generation, whose teeth \add are as\add* swords, and their jaw-teeth \add as\add* knives, to devour the poor from off the earth, and the needy from \add among\add* men. 
\v 15 The horse-leech hath two daughters, \add crying\add* , Give, give. There are three \add things that\add* are never satisfied, \add yes\add* , four \add things\add* say not, \add It is\add* enough: 
\v 16 The grave; and the barren womb; the earth \add that\add* is not filled with water; and the fire \add that\add* saith not, \add It is\add* enough. 
\v 17 The eye \add that\add* mocketh at \add its\add* father, and despiseth to obey \add its\add* mother, the ravens of the valley shall pick it out, and the young eagles shall eat it. 
\v 18 There are three \add things which\add* are too wonderful for me, yes, four which I know not: 
\v 19 The way of an eagle in the air; the way of a serpent upon a rock; the way of a ship in the midst of the sea; and the way of a man with a maid. 
\v 20 Such \add is\add* the way of an adulterous woman; she eateth, and wipeth her mouth, and saith, I have done no wickedness. 
\v 21 For three \add things\add* the earth is disquieted, and for four \add which\add* it cannot bear: 
\v 22 For a servant when he reigneth; and a fool when he is filled with food. 
\v 23 For an odious \add woman\add* when she is married; and a handmaid that is heir to her mistress. 
\v 24 There are four \add things which are\add* little upon the earth, but they \add are\add* very wise: 
\v 25 The ants \add are\add* a people not strong, yet they prepare their food in the summer; 
\v 26 The conies \add are but\add* a feeble people, yet they make their houses in the rocks; 
\v 27 The locusts have no king, yet go they forth all of them by bands; 
\v 28 The spider taketh hold with her hands, and is in king's palaces. 
\v 29 There are three \add things\add* which go well, yes, four are comely in going: 
\v 30 A lion, \add which is\add* strongest among beasts, and turneth not away for any; 
\v 31 A greyhound; a he-goat also; and a king, against whom \add there is\add* no rising up. 
\v 32 If thou hast done foolishly in lifting up thyself, or if thou hast thought evil, \add lay\add* thy hand upon thy mouth. 
\v 33 Surely the churning of milk bringeth forth butter, and the wringing of the nose bringeth forth blood: so the forcing of wrath bringeth forth strife. 
\c 31  
\p
\v 1 The words of king Lemuel, the prophecy that his mother taught him. 
\v 2 What, my son? and what, the son of my womb? and what, the son of my vows? 
\v 3 Give not thy strength to women, nor thy ways to that which destroyeth kings. 
\v 4  \add It is\add* not for kings, O Lemuel, \add it is\add* not for kings to drink wine; nor for princes strong drink: 
\v 5 Lest they drink, and forget the law, and pervert the judgment of any of the afflicted. 
\v 6 Give strong drink to him that is ready to perish, and wine to those that are of heavy hearts. 
\v 7 Let him drink, and forget his poverty, and remember his misery no more. 
\v 8 Open thy mouth for the dumb in the cause of all such as are appointed to destruction. 
\v 9 Open thy mouth, judge righteously, and plead the cause of the poor and needy. 
\v 10 Who can find a virtuous woman? for her price \add is\add* far above rubies. 
\v 11 The heart of her husband doth safely trust in her, so that he shall have no need of spoil. 
\v 12 She will do him good and not evil all the days of her life. 
\v 13 She seeketh wool, and flax, and worketh willingly with her hands. 
\v 14 She is like the merchant's ships; she bringeth her food from afar. 
\v 15 She riseth also while it is yet night, and giveth food to her household, and a portion to her maidens. 
\v 16 She considereth a field, and buyeth it: with the fruit of her hands she planteth a vineyard. 
\v 17 She girdeth her loins with strength, and strengtheneth her arms. 
\v 18 She perceiveth that her merchandise \add is\add* good: her candle goeth not out by night. 
\v 19 She layeth her hands to the spindle, and her hands hold the distaff. 
\v 20 She stretcheth out her hand to the poor; yes, she reacheth forth her hands to the needy. 
\v 21 She is not afraid of the snow for her household: for all her household \add are\add* clothed with scarlet. 
\v 22 She maketh herself coverings of tapestry; her clothing \add is\add* silk and purple. 
\v 23 Her husband is known in the gates, when he sitteth among the elders of the land. 
\v 24 She maketh fine linen, and selleth \add it\add* ; and delivereth girdles to the merchant. 
\v 25 Strength and honor \add are\add* her clothing; and she shall rejoice in time to come. 
\v 26 She openeth her mouth with wisdom; and on her tongue \add is\add* the law of kindness. 
\v 27 She looketh well to the ways of her household, and eateth not the bread of idleness. 
\v 28 Her children rise up, and call her blessed; her husband \add also\add* , and he praiseth her. 
\v 29 Many daughters have done virtuously, but thou excellest them all. 
\v 30 Favor \add is\add* deceitful, and beauty \add is\add* vain: \add but\add* a woman \add that\add* feareth the LORD, she shall be praised. 
\v 31 Give her of the fruit of her hands; and let her own works praise her in the gates. 